The paper deals with a data structure called the \(k^d\)-tree, which is used to represent binary relations in a compact form. This is a topic in data structures (cs.DS) and databases (cs.DB). The paper also discusses the use of Morton codes, which are commonly used in computational geometry (cs.CG). The paper proposes a new approach to interpreting the \(k^d\)-tree, which involves dynamic tries, a topic in data compression (cs.DC) and combinatorics (cs.CC).
